tion in Romania, 1918–1944 -- tThe Eugenic Fortress: Alfred Csallner and the Saxon Eugenic Discourse in Interwar Romania -- tFighting the White Plague: Demography and Abortion in the Independent State of Croatia -- tPART IV: New Research Agendas -- tRemapping the Historiography of Modernization and State-Building in Southeastern Europe through Health, Hygiene and Eugenics -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume is a collection of chapters that deal with issues of health, hygiene and eugenics in Southeastern Europe to 1945, specifically, in Bosnia-Herzegovina, Bulgaria, Croatia, Greece and Romania. Its major concern is to examine the transfer of medical ideas to society via local, national and international agencies and to show in how far developments in public health, preventive medicine, social hygiene, welfare, gender relations and eugenics followed a regional pattern. This volume provides insights into a region that has to date been marginal to scholarship of the social history of medicine.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aEugenicszBalkan PeninsulaxHistory. 0aPublic healthzBalkan PeninsulaxHistory. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh  aEugenics, Medical policy, Modernization, Public health, Racism, Social medicine, State-building.1 aBucur, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDugac, Željko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuchs, Brigitte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGardikas, Katerina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeorgescu, Tudor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarakatsani, Despina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id